<TopicInfo Title="Numerical Integration" Subtitle="Approximate ∫f(x)dx over [a, b]">
    <div>
        <p class="topic-info__overview">
            Numerical integration (quadrature) approximates the definite integral
            $\int_a^b f(x)\,dx$ by summing weighted function evaluations over
            sub-intervals. More sub-intervals $n$ reduces the error.
        </p>

        <div class="topic-info__cards">
            <div class="topic-info__card">
                <h3>Rectangle Rule</h3>
                <div class="topic-info__formula">$$\int_a^b f(x)\,dx \approx h \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} f(x_i^*), \quad h = \frac{b-a}{n}$$</div>
                <p>Approximates each sub-interval with a rectangle. Three variants:
                    left ($x_i^* = x_i$), right ($x_i^* = x_{i+1}$), midpoint ($x_i^* = x_i + h/2$).
                    Midpoint is $O(h^2)$; left and right are $O(h)$.</p>
                <p class="topic-info__limitation">Low accuracy for rapidly varying functions with few intervals.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="topic-info__card">
                <h3>Trapezoidal Rule</h3>
                <div class="topic-info__formula">$$\int_a^b f(x)\,dx \approx \frac{h}{2}\!\left[f(a) + 2\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}f(x_i) + f(b)\right]$$</div>
                <p>Approximates each strip with a trapezoid. $O(h^2)$ accuracy.
                    Easy to implement and more accurate than the basic rectangle rule.</p>
                <p class="topic-info__limitation">Exact only for linear functions; performs poorly for oscillatory integrands.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="topic-info__card">
                <h3>Simpson's 1/3 Rule</h3>
                <div class="topic-info__formula">$$\int_a^b f(x)\,dx \approx \frac{h}{3}\!\left[f(a) + 4\sum_{\text{odd}} f(x_i) + 2\sum_{\text{even}} f(x_i) + f(b)\right]$$</div>
                <p>Fits a quadratic through each pair of sub-intervals. $O(h^4)$ accuracy —
                    a big leap over the trapezoid rule. Requires an even number of intervals.</p>
                <p class="topic-info__limitation">Requires even $n$ (auto-corrected); exact only for polynomials up to degree 3.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</TopicInfo>